DESCRIPTION:Gathering Weather Data – GEOG 155 Major Assignment\n\nHow muc
 h do you currently know about how the temperature changes over the semeste
 r? Is it like historical changes? What does the recorded data say about yo
 ur prediction and the historical record?\n\nThis assignment will help you 
 understand how to make a hypothesis\, gather data and interpret results. E
 ach student will make a prediction about the temperature outside each week
  and record their estimated guess. Then\, you will measure the actual temp
 erature during the entire semester and compare your results with your gues
 ses and historical data. You’ll use Microsoft Excel to keep track of the
  data and make graphs and Microsoft Word to write up a short report of you
 r findings.\n\nThis is the signature assignment that in part satisfies the
  ACE 4 requirement for this course.\n\nDirections:\n\nPart 1 – Due 01/16
 /26\, 11:59pm\n\nData collection (Week 1) starts the week of Jan. 19th\n\n
 Data collection stops (Week 12) the week of April 13th\n\nSkip the week of
  Spring Break\n\n* Create an Excel spreadsheet with a file name: “YOURLA
 STNAME_Spring26_WxData”\n\n* Create 12 rows and four columns.\n\n* Label
  the rows “[date]”. (you’ll enter in the date of your lab)\n\n* Labe
 l the columns “Predicted Temp (F)\, Actual Temp (F)\, Historic Temp (F)\
 , and Notes”\n\nUse any style you like\, but make sure it looks basicall
 y something like this:\n\n \n\nThen\, fill in the temperature you think i
 t will be starting the week of January 19th (Week 1). Week 2 should be you
 r predicted temperature for the week of January 26th\, and so on...\n\nYou
  should record the temperature that you think it will be at the beginning 
 of your lab. So\, if your lab starts at 2:30pm\, your predicted temp shoul
 d reflect that temperature you predict. Your recorded temperatures will be
  measured at the beginning of your lab period each week. There is no wrong
  answer for the “Predicted Temp” column\, and you should not use any w
 eather app\, website\, etc... to fill in this information. It is intended 
 to be a guess\, based on what you assume the temp to be.\n\nWhat to turn i
 n: your excel spreadsheet uploaded to Canvas\, with your predictions. Done
  properly\, this will receive 25 points.\n\nPart 2 – Due 04/24/26\, 11:5
 9pm\n\nEach week for 12 weeks\, at the beginning of your lab\, you’ll re
 cord the temperature in degrees Fahrenheit. After you have recorded your f
 inal temperature\, navigate to Weather Underground’s website for histori
 cal data in Lincoln\, NE: https://www.wunderground.com/history/daily/us/ne
 /lincoln/KLNK/date/1981-9-1\n\nRecord the historical temperature at the sa
 me time and date\, but from 1991.\n\nCreate a graph\, using Excel\, that s
 hows Temperature (F) on the y axis\, and time on the x axis. Make sure to 
 display the three variables in different colors\, your predicted temperatu
 re (green)\, the actual temperature (red)\, and the historic temperature (
 blue) from 1981.\n\nMake your graph easy to read:\n\n* Make a title\n\n* L
 abel your axes\n\n* Use other design tools as you please\n\nCopy and paste
  this graph into a Word document. Your Word document will be a project rep
 ort about the data. Your report should have a heading\, your name\, class\
 , lab time\, and date.\n\nIn short essay form (using complete sentences an
 d grammar) answer the following questions in your report:\n\n* Generally\,
  what does your data show?\n\n* Did anything surprise you about the data?\
 n\n* Discuss the veracity of your predictions.\n\n* What informed your pre
 dictions?\n\n* How does the historic record compare?\n\n* What might expla
 in the differences in your data?\n\nUse 10 or 12-point\, 1.5-2.0 spaced fo
 nt. Report should be no longer than one page\, including the graph. The wr
 ite-up\, the graph\, and the headings for the report should all fit on one
  page.\n\nWhat to turn in: this report\, to Canvas. 25 points for the grap
 h\, 25 points for the write-up\, and 25 points for overall quality.
